B044C017V023	44	17	23	For, as I passed along, and beheld the objects of your worship, I found an altar with this inscription, To the Unknown God: Him, therefore, you ignorantly worship, I announce to you.
B044C017V024	44	17	24	The God who made the world, and all things that are in it, being the Lord of heaven and earth, dwells not in temples made with hands:
B044C017V025	44	17	25	Neither is he served by human hands, as if he stood in need of anything; he himself giving to all, life, and breath, and all things.
B044C017V026	44	17	26	And he has made of one blood, the whole race of men, to inhabit all the face of the earth; having marked out the times previously arranged in order, and the boundaries of their habitations:
B044C017V027	44	17	27	that they might seek after the Lord, if possibly they might feel after him, and find him; though he be not far from every one of us:
B044C017V028	44	17	28	«for in him we live, and are moved, and do exist; as some of your own poets have said-For we his offspring are.»
B044C017V029	44	17	29	We, therefore, being the offspring of God, ought not to imagine the Deity to be like gold, or silver, or stone, wrought by the art and contrivance of man.
