B044C023V025	44	23	25	And he wrote an epistle, the contents of which are in this copy:
B044C023V026	44	23	26	Claudius Lysias, to his excellency, Felix, the governor, sends greeting:
B044C023V027	44	23	27	This man was seized by the Jews, and had like to have been slain by them; when I came with a party of soldiers, and rescued him: and I have since learned, that he is a Roman.
B044C023V028	44	23	28	And, desiring to know the crime of which they accused him, I brought him before the Sanhedrim,
B044C023V029	44	23	29	whom I found to be accused concerning questions of their law, but to have nothing charged upon him worthy of death, or of bonds.
B044C023V030	44	23	30	But when it was signified to me, that an ambush would be laid for the man, by the Jews, I immediately sent him to you, commanding his accusers also to declare before you, what they have against him. Farewell.
